metadata.name: Mandala "Celestial Harmony" #4
metadata.description:
Discover the mesmerizing world of "Celestial Harmony," a generative art collection where ancient symbolism meets modern digital creativity. This series, crafted for fxhash, invites art collectors to explore the profound beauty of mandalas through intricate, algorithmically generated designs that evoke balance, unity, and spiritual depth.

What is a Mandala?
The mandala, derived from the ancient Sanskrit word for "circle," is a sacred symbol found across cultures, from Tibetan Buddhism to Native American traditions. It represents the universe, wholeness, and the journey toward inner harmony. Traditionally, mandalas are symmetrical, geometric patterns that radiate from a central point, often used in meditation to focus the mind and connect with the divine. Their hypnotic designs draw the viewer inward, offering a sense of peace and contemplation.

In this collection, each mandala is a unique, algorithmically generated masterpiece, blending traditional symmetry with contemporary aesthetics. The artworks feature:
•	Dynamic Layers and Patterns: Multiple layers of petals, waves, spirals, and radial forms create a sense of depth and motion, drawing the eye toward the center.
•	Harmonious Color Palettes: Choose from six distinct styles, ranging from soft pastels (blues, pinks, mint greens) to vibrant triadic hues (red, green, blue) and bold complementary tones (purple and yellow). Each palette is carefully curated to evoke emotional resonance—whether calming, energizing, or grounding.
•	Central Flower Motif: At the heart of each mandala blooms a delicate flower, symbolizing growth and renewal, surrounded by intricate, symmetrical patterns that radiate outward like cosmic energy.
•	Subtle Variations: Small, intentional imperfections in symmetry and curvature add an organic, handcrafted feel, making each piece feel alive and unique.

metadata.name: Modern Times #122
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: tur1ng #8
metadata.description:
‘tur1ng’ consists of audible image architectures based on the principle of Turing machines. These systems are mathematical models of computation that manipulate symbols on a strip of tape according to a table of rules. The machine first writes a symbol in a cell on the tape, then either moves the tape one cell left or right, then, based on the observed symbol and the machine's own state in the table, either proceeds to another instruction or halts computation.

In ‘tur1ng’, rules are stored as colors and the original tape cells are constructed from a two dimensional array. The sound unfolds as the algorithm proceeds: monitoring these binary songs requires being attentive to changes in the state or behavior of the system over time so that appropriate interventions or other process-related activities may be carried out. Another feature of listening algorithms is that it often has to be done as a background or secondary task or, perhaps, in parallel with one or more other primary tasks.

Touch to listen.

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #390
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #117
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Flippr #120
metadata.description:
Experiments in 3D, moiré, monochrome and flipping planes.

Around 600.000 pixels, all black planes rotating on their own axis. 
The angle of rotation will define the contrast and create different images over time.

Zoom in and move around to explore each pixel and its movement in detail.

On some rare occasions the pixels are white and background is black.

December 2021, Berlin
by @bgola

Rebuilding linear perspective from the ground up to generate improbable structures. Variations use one-point, two-point or three-point perspective, structures are rendered as lines, planes and volumes, colors are limited to ⬛🟥⬜!
